2
00:00:33,390 --> 00:00:36,508
[♪ choir sings "Psalm 23,
The Lord's My Shepherd"]

3
00:00:37,270 --> 00:00:42,299
♪ He makes me down to lie

4
00:00:42,430 --> 00:00:47,948
♪ In pastures green he leadeth me

5
00:00:48,070 --> 00:00:53,543
♪ The quiet waters by

6
00:00:53,670 --> 00:00:59,268
♪ He leadeth me

7
00:00:59,390 --> 00:01:05,738
♪ The quiet waters by ♪

8
00:01:08,109 --> 00:01:10,749
♪ have received of the Lord

9
00:01:10,869 --> 00:01:13,338
that which also I delivered onto you.

10
00:01:14,348 --> 00:01:19,741
The Lord Jesus, the same night
in which he was betrayed, took bread,

11
00:01:19,869 --> 00:01:22,338
and when he had given thanks,

12
00:01:22,469 --> 00:01:25,860
he broke it and said,

13
00:01:25,988 --> 00:01:29,345
"Take. Eat.

14
00:01:29,509 --> 00:01:32,262
"This is my body,

15
00:01:32,428 --> 00:01:34,261
"which is broken for you,

16
00:01:35,068 --> 00:01:37,583
"this do in remembrance of me."

17
00:01:38,829 --> 00:01:41,901
And after the same manner
he also took the cup

18
00:01:42,029 --> 00:01:43,905
when he had eaten, saying,

19
00:01:44,829 --> 00:01:48,298
"This cup is the new covenant
in my blood.

20
00:01:48,428 --> 00:01:51,660
"This, oft as you drink it,
in remembrance of me,

21
00:01:51,788 --> 00:01:54,258
"or as often as you eat this bread

22
00:01:54,389 --> 00:01:57,381
"and drink this wine,

23
00:01:57,509 --> 00:02:00,387
"you do shew the Lord's death

24
00:02:00,509 --> 00:02:02,261
"till he comes again."

25
00:02:14,830 --> 00:02:17,344
[♪ traditional pipes play]

26
00:02:51,950 --> 00:02:55,341
[woman sings] ♪ Oh, I am come

27
00:02:55,510 --> 00:02:59,469
♪ To the north country

28
00:02:59,589 --> 00:03:06,383
[chorus] ♪ Ochon, ochon, ochrie!

29
00:03:09,029 --> 00:03:12,738
[woman's solo] ♪ Without a penny

30
00:03:12,869 --> 00:03:16,704
♪ In my purse

31
00:03:16,830 --> 00:03:21,540
♪ To buy a meal

32
00:03:21,670 --> 00:03:26,426
♪ For me

33
00:03:27,550 --> 00:03:34,627
♪ One time I had a hundred sheep

34
00:03:34,749 --> 00:03:41,940
[chorus] ♪ Ochon, ochon, ochrie!

35
00:03:44,670 --> 00:03:52,225
[solo] ♪ Skipping o'er yon narrow creek

36
00:03:52,350 --> 00:03:58,824
♪ And growing wool for me ♪

37
00:04:01,910 --> 00:04:04,424
[♪ PAUL GIOVANNI: "Corn Rigs"]

38
00:04:08,910 --> 00:04:12,345
♪ It was upon a lammas night

39
00:04:12,469 --> 00:04:15,940
♪ When corn rigs are bonnie

40
00:04:16,069 --> 00:04:19,425
♪ Beneath the moon's unclouded light

41
00:04:19,548 --> 00:04:22,940
♪ I held a while to Annie

42
00:04:23,068 --> 00:04:26,824
♪ The time went by with careless heed

43
00:04:26,949 --> 00:04:31,738
♪ Till 'tween the late and early

44
00:04:31,868 --> 00:04:35,827
♪ With small persuasion she agreed

45
00:04:35,949 --> 00:04:40,705
♪ To see me through the barley

46
00:04:42,349 --> 00:04:44,659
♪ Corn rigs and barley rigs

47
00:04:44,830 --> 00:04:50,380
♪ And corn rigs are bonnie

48
00:04:50,508 --> 00:04:54,264
♪ I'll not forget that happy night

49
00:04:54,389 --> 00:05:00,145
♪ Among the rigs with Annie...

50
00:05:14,029 --> 00:05:16,383
[engine stops]

51
00:05:25,909 --> 00:05:28,629
Will you send a dinghy, please?

52
00:05:32,188 --> 00:05:35,419
'Did you hear me?
I'd like a dinghy, if you please.'

53
00:05:37,469 --> 00:05:41,666
Hello, sir!
Have you lost your bearings?

54
00:05:41,789 --> 00:05:44,065
[Howie] 'No, sir, I don't think so.

55
00:05:44,188 --> 00:05:47,979
- 'This is Summerisle, is it not?'
- It is, sir!

56
00:05:48,109 --> 00:05:51,022
'I'm right then.
Now, would you send a dinghy, please?'

57
00:05:51,149 --> 00:05:55,904
I'm afraid it can't be done, sir!
This is private property!

58
00:05:56,029 --> 00:05:59,863
You can't land here
without written permission!

59
00:06:00,789 --> 00:06:03,782
'I, as you can see, am a police officer.

60
00:06:03,949 --> 00:06:06,020
'A complaint has been registered

61
00:06:06,149 --> 00:06:09,426
'by a resident of this island
about a missing child.

62
00:06:09,548 --> 00:06:13,462
'Now, that makes it a police matter,
private property or not.

63
00:06:13,589 --> 00:06:16,058
'Now, will you send a dinghy, please?'

64
00:06:16,188 --> 00:06:18,145
Need to tell his lordship, aye.

65
00:06:27,909 --> 00:06:30,344
♪ Corn rigs and barley rigs

66
00:06:30,469 --> 00:06:34,666
♪ And corn rigs are bonnie

67
00:06:35,949 --> 00:06:39,830
♪ I'll not forget that happy night

68
00:06:39,949 --> 00:06:44,342
♪ Among the rigs with Annie...

69
00:06:59,589 --> 00:07:02,421
Good day to you, sir.
I'm the harbour master.

70
00:07:02,589 --> 00:07:04,738
Sergeant Howie, West Highland police.

71
00:07:04,868 --> 00:07:07,383
A missing child is always trouble.

72
00:07:07,508 --> 00:07:10,467
Aye, aye, aye, for everybody.

73
00:07:10,589 --> 00:07:13,742
Perhaps you would be good enough
to explain matters to his lordship.

74
00:07:13,868 --> 00:07:16,065
He's most particular who lands here.

75
00:07:16,229 --> 00:07:19,859
All in good time.
We, too, have our own particularities.

76
00:07:19,988 --> 00:07:23,187
You know her?
Her name is Rowan Morrison.

77
00:07:24,428 --> 00:07:28,137
The photo was in this letter,
posted here on Summerisle.

78
00:07:28,270 --> 00:07:30,623
No, no, never seen her before.

79
00:07:30,748 --> 00:07:34,104
I don't know the face either.
Do you know her, Kenny?

80
00:07:34,229 --> 00:07:36,505
She doesn't belong to this island.

81
00:07:36,629 --> 00:07:39,017
No, I never saw her before.

82
00:07:39,149 --> 00:07:42,267
No, she doesn't belong here at all.
Johnnie?

83
00:07:42,389 --> 00:07:44,222
[Howie] The letter is anonymous.

84
00:07:44,349 --> 00:07:47,705
It was addressed to me personally
on the mainland.

85
00:07:47,830 --> 00:07:50,183
No, cannae say I know her.

86
00:07:50,308 --> 00:07:54,303
Now, now, what are you saying?
You're saying she's not from the island?

87
00:07:54,428 --> 00:07:56,500
That's right. She's not from here.

88
00:07:56,629 --> 00:08:00,258
You get Morrisons on Lewis
and a few on Mull. I would try there.

89
00:08:00,389 --> 00:08:01,824
Thanks.

90
00:08:02,709 --> 00:08:07,226
"None of us has seen May Morrison's
daughter Rowan since last year.

91
00:08:07,349 --> 00:08:11,467
"She's only 12, and she's been missing
from her home for many months."

92
00:08:11,589 --> 00:08:13,580
The mother's name is May Morrison.

93
00:08:13,709 --> 00:08:17,464
Oh, May!
She quite slipped my memory.

94
00:08:17,589 --> 00:08:20,979
Of course we've got May. She keeps
the post office in the high street.

95
00:08:21,109 --> 00:08:24,147
- May Morrison? You're quite sure?
- Quite sure.

96
00:08:24,270 --> 00:08:26,657
Well, thank you for your help.

97
00:08:28,909 --> 00:08:32,028
That's not May's daughter, though!

98
00:08:33,989 --> 00:08:36,345
No, she's not May's.

99
00:08:36,470 --> 00:08:38,586
[Howie] Then who is she?

100
00:08:48,269 --> 00:08:51,899
♪ The sky was blue,
the wind was still

101
00:08:52,029 --> 00:08:55,784
♪ The moon was shining clearly

102
00:08:55,909 --> 00:08:59,140
♪ I set her down with right good will

103
00:08:59,269 --> 00:09:02,979
♪ Among the rigs of barley

104
00:09:03,110 --> 00:09:06,659
♪ I kenned her heart with all my own

105
00:09:06,789 --> 00:09:10,987
♪ I loved her most sincerely

106
00:09:12,069 --> 00:09:15,664
♪ I kissed her o'er and o'er again

107
00:09:15,789 --> 00:09:19,145
♪ Among the rigs of barley...

108
00:09:31,510 --> 00:09:33,547
[door bell tinkles]

109
00:09:40,309 --> 00:09:43,109
[May] Good afternoon.
[Howie] I like your rabbits.

110
00:09:43,230 --> 00:09:46,302
[May] Those are hares,
not silly old rabbits.

111
00:09:46,429 --> 00:09:50,582
Lovely March hares.
Can I help you?

112
00:09:50,710 --> 00:09:52,939
- Mrs Morrison? Mrs May Morrison?
- Yes.

113
00:09:53,069 --> 00:09:56,904
- Sergeant Howie, West Highland police.
- Oh, my!

114
00:09:57,029 --> 00:10:00,182
Did you come over in that aeroplane
that I saw flying round?

115
00:10:00,350 --> 00:10:03,706
- Aye, that's right.
- What, just to see me?

116
00:10:03,830 --> 00:10:06,742
Well, no, not exactly. Erm...

117
00:10:06,870 --> 00:10:10,750
I'm making inquiries about your daughter.
We understand that she's missing.

118
00:10:10,870 --> 00:10:12,986
Missing? My daughter?

119
00:10:14,470 --> 00:10:17,462
- Aye. You do have a daughter?
- Yes.

120
00:10:17,590 --> 00:10:22,106
- And that's her?
- Oh, never.

121
00:10:22,230 --> 00:10:23,379
[giggles]

122
00:10:23,510 --> 00:10:25,706
I tell you no.

123
00:10:28,390 --> 00:10:30,859
I think you'd better come with me.

124
00:10:32,230 --> 00:10:36,303
This is our Myrtle.
She was nine last Thursday.

125
00:10:36,470 --> 00:10:39,063
She's not a bit like the girl
in your photograph.

126
00:10:39,189 --> 00:10:42,068
She must be
at least 13 or 14, surely.

127
00:10:42,189 --> 00:10:44,579
Myrtle, say hello.

128
00:10:44,710 --> 00:10:47,178
- This is Sergeant... Oh!
- Howie.

129
00:10:47,309 --> 00:10:49,187
- Oh.
- Hello, Myrtle.

130
00:10:49,309 --> 00:10:50,869
How do you do?

131
00:10:51,029 --> 00:10:53,862
- Look, Mummy, I'm drawing a hare.
- Ah.

132
00:10:54,029 --> 00:10:55,748
[doorbell chimes]

133
00:10:55,909 --> 00:10:58,220
[May] Excuse me, Sergeant.

134
00:11:09,390 --> 00:11:10,903
Hello.

135
00:11:13,590 --> 00:11:16,866
Here you are,
you can fill in the ears in grey.

136
00:11:16,990 --> 00:11:18,389
Oh, sorry.

137
00:11:20,069 --> 00:11:22,140
Thank you, Myrtle.

138
00:11:26,309 --> 00:11:30,827
Myrtle, do you, erm...
do you know Rowan?

139
00:11:30,950 --> 00:11:32,782
Course I do.

140
00:11:34,309 --> 00:11:37,587
- You do?
- Course I do, silly.

141
00:11:41,029 --> 00:11:44,260
- Uh, do you know where she is now?
- In the fields.

142
00:11:44,390 --> 00:11:46,461
She runs and plays there all day.

143
00:11:46,590 --> 00:11:49,503
[Howie] Does she? Do you think
she'll be coming back for tea?

144
00:11:49,669 --> 00:11:52,822
Tea? Hares don't have tea, silly.

145
00:11:54,870 --> 00:11:56,383
Hares?

146
00:11:56,550 --> 00:12:00,702
She's a hare. Rowan's a hare.
She has a lovely time.

147
00:12:02,189 --> 00:12:04,260
- Well, tell me...
- Well, now, Sergeant.

148
00:12:04,390 --> 00:12:07,109
You will stay and have a cup of tea,
won't you?

149
00:12:07,269 --> 00:12:09,864
- Oh, well, yes, yes, please.
- Good.

150
00:12:09,990 --> 00:12:11,741
- That's very kind of you.
- Not at all.

151
00:12:11,870 --> 00:12:14,338
It must be thirsty work,
asking all those questions, eh?

152
00:12:14,470 --> 00:12:15,699
Aye.

153
00:12:19,189 --> 00:12:21,260
[♪ accordion music playing]

154
00:12:25,429 --> 00:12:28,149
[lively chatter and laughter]

155
00:12:29,470 --> 00:12:31,700
[conversation and music stop]

156
00:12:31,830 --> 00:12:33,901
- Hello. Evening.
- Evening.

157
00:12:35,470 --> 00:12:37,825
- Evening.
- Hello again.

158
00:12:39,269 --> 00:12:43,024
- Are you the landlord here?
- Aye. I'm Alder MacGreagor.

159
00:12:43,149 --> 00:12:45,619
And you must be the policeman
from the mainland.

160
00:12:45,750 --> 00:12:48,503
Aye, that's right. Sergeant Howie,
West Highland constabulary.

161
00:12:48,630 --> 00:12:51,587
I'm quite obviously not going
to get back to the mainland tonight,

162
00:12:51,710 --> 00:12:53,939
so I wondered if you had a room
and a bite of supper I could have.

163
00:12:54,110 --> 00:12:57,228
- Could you manage that?
- Aye, I think that can be arranged.

164
00:12:57,350 --> 00:13:00,581
My daughter Willow will show you
to your room.

165
00:13:00,710 --> 00:13:04,179
- Willow!
- Father?

166
00:13:04,309 --> 00:13:07,826
This is Sergeant Howie,
a policeman from the mainland,

167
00:13:07,950 --> 00:13:10,226
who will be spending the night with us.

168
00:13:10,350 --> 00:13:14,308
- This is my daughter, Willow.
- Good evening.

169
00:13:14,429 --> 00:13:16,420
Show the Sergeant to his room,
would you?

170
00:13:16,590 --> 00:13:18,228
[whistles and laughter]

171
00:13:18,350 --> 00:13:21,068
♪ Much has been said
of the strumpets of yore

172
00:13:21,189 --> 00:13:24,865
♪ Of wenches and bawdy house queens
by the score

173
00:13:24,990 --> 00:13:28,904
♪ But I sing of a baggage
that we all adore

174
00:13:29,029 --> 00:13:32,580
♪ The landlord's daughter

175
00:13:32,710 --> 00:13:36,669
♪ You'll never love another

176
00:13:36,789 --> 00:13:40,544
♪ Although she's not the kind of girl

177
00:13:40,669 --> 00:13:43,503
♪ To take home to your mother

178
00:13:43,630 --> 00:13:45,939
[raucous laughter]

179
00:13:48,110 --> 00:13:51,625
♪ Her ale, it is lively and strong
to the taste

180
00:13:51,789 --> 00:13:55,499
♪ It is brewed with discretion,
never with haste

181
00:13:55,669 --> 00:13:59,583
♪ You can have all you like
if you swear not to waste

182
00:13:59,710 --> 00:14:03,340
♪ The landlord's daughter

183
00:14:03,510 --> 00:14:06,821
♪ And when her name is mentioned

184
00:14:06,950 --> 00:14:12,502
♪ The parts of every gentleman
do stand up

185
00:14:12,630 --> 00:14:13,984
♪ At attention

186
00:14:18,550 --> 00:14:22,179
♪ Oh, nothing can delight so

187
00:14:22,309 --> 00:14:27,669
- ♪ As does the part that lies between
- ♪ Her left toe

188
00:14:27,830 --> 00:14:29,707
♪ And her right toe

189
00:14:47,630 --> 00:14:52,021
- I'd like my supper now, please.
- It won't be long, Sergeant.

190
00:14:52,149 --> 00:14:54,664
Och, you don't want to let them
worry you.

191
00:14:54,789 --> 00:14:56,939
Why don't you have a wee drink?

192
00:14:57,069 --> 00:14:59,346
No, thank you, not just now.

193
00:14:59,470 --> 00:15:01,063
[Howie knocks on bar]

194
00:15:03,830 --> 00:15:05,866
[quiet descends]

195
00:15:07,990 --> 00:15:12,540
I think you all ought to know that
I am here on official business.

196
00:15:13,870 --> 00:15:18,023
I am here to investigate
the disappearance of a young girl...

197
00:15:19,309 --> 00:15:22,029
...as doubtless, the harbour master
has already told you by now.

198
00:15:22,149 --> 00:15:26,109
There's the girl.
Her name is Rowan Morrison.

199
00:15:26,230 --> 00:15:29,904
Would you pass that
among your customers, please?

200
00:15:30,029 --> 00:15:33,385
Now, if any of you can give me
any idea as to her whereabouts,

201
00:15:33,510 --> 00:15:36,263
I'd be most grateful
if you'd let me know.

202
00:15:36,390 --> 00:15:38,461
[indistinct muttering]

203
00:15:39,789 --> 00:15:42,669
[man] No, I've not seen her.
Have you tried the mainland?

204
00:15:42,789 --> 00:15:47,260
[woman] No, I've not see her.
I've not seen her at all.

205
00:15:49,309 --> 00:15:53,702
[MacGreagor] No, I'm afraid
nobody's seen her, Sergeant.

206
00:15:59,149 --> 00:16:02,665
Thank you. Are these
harvest festival photographs?

207
00:16:02,789 --> 00:16:05,178
Aye, we have one taken
at the end of every summer.

208
00:16:05,309 --> 00:16:09,144
- What happened to last year's?
- It got broke.

209
00:16:09,269 --> 00:16:11,385
Your supper's ready, Sergeant.

210
00:16:11,510 --> 00:16:14,149
Willow, show the Sergeant
to the dining room.

211
00:16:15,630 --> 00:16:17,223
Thank you.

212
00:16:21,029 --> 00:16:22,509
It's disgusting.

213
00:16:25,069 --> 00:16:27,380
- Thank you.
- What's the matter, aren't you hungry?

214
00:16:27,510 --> 00:16:29,420
Aye, it's just most of the food I've had,

215
00:16:29,550 --> 00:16:34,624
the farmhouse soup, the potatoes,
broad beans, all come out of a can.

216
00:16:34,789 --> 00:16:39,659
Broad beans, in their natural state,
aren't usually turquoise, are they?

217
00:16:39,789 --> 00:16:43,943
Some things in their natural state
have the most vivid colours.

218
00:16:46,309 --> 00:16:48,984
I-I-l...just wanted to know why,
that's all.

219
00:16:49,110 --> 00:16:52,386
Now, I wonder what
you'll be wanting for afters?

220
00:16:52,510 --> 00:16:55,582
- I'll have an apple.
- No apples.

221
00:16:56,909 --> 00:17:00,585
No apples? On an island famous
for its fruit and vegetables?

222
00:17:00,710 --> 00:17:03,099
I expect they've all been exported.

223
00:17:03,230 --> 00:17:05,583
You can have peaches and cream,
if you like.

224
00:17:05,708 --> 00:17:08,425
Aye, from a can, I suppose.

225
00:17:08,550 --> 00:17:10,223
All right.

226
00:17:12,108 --> 00:17:15,579
Cheer up.
Food isn't everything in life, you know.

227
00:17:34,869 --> 00:17:37,942
[sensuous moaning]

228
00:18:20,148 --> 00:18:22,265
[sobbing]

229
00:18:28,949 --> 00:18:31,064
up, up, up,

230
00:18:31,189 --> 00:18:34,387
up, up, up! up! up!

231
00:18:34,510 --> 00:18:36,387
[cheering and clapping]

232
00:18:45,990 --> 00:18:47,185
Where?

233
00:18:47,310 --> 00:18:50,619
You'll find it at the top of the stair
on your right.

234
00:18:54,070 --> 00:18:56,664
[singing and laughter]

235
00:19:02,429 --> 00:19:08,141
♪ I put my hand on her knee

236
00:19:08,270 --> 00:19:10,908
♪ And she said

237
00:19:11,070 --> 00:19:13,379
♪ Do you want to see

238
00:19:14,030 --> 00:19:19,628
- ♪ I put my hand on her breast
- Willow MacGreagor!

239
00:19:19,750 --> 00:19:22,503
♪ And she said

240
00:19:22,629 --> 00:19:25,270
♪ Do you want to kiss... ♪

241
00:19:25,389 --> 00:19:29,622
Willow MacGreagor, I have the honour
to present to you Ash Buchanan.

242
00:19:30,350 --> 00:19:32,737
Come up, Ash Buchanan.

243
00:19:35,669 --> 00:19:37,581
Another sacrifice for Aphrodite, Willow.

244
00:19:37,708 --> 00:19:39,860
You flatter me, your lordship.

245
00:19:39,990 --> 00:19:42,379
Surely you mean to Aphrodite?

246
00:19:42,510 --> 00:19:43,658
I make no such distinction.

247
00:19:43,790 --> 00:19:46,350
You are the Goddess of Love
in human form

248
00:19:46,468 --> 00:19:47,983
and I am merely your humble acolyte.

249
00:19:50,030 --> 00:19:52,829
Enjoy yourself... and him.

250
00:19:52,949 --> 00:19:56,022
Only, make sure you are ready
for tomorrow's tomorrow.

251
00:19:56,148 --> 00:19:59,744
The day of
death and rebirth.

252
00:20:00,550 --> 00:20:01,619
Yes.

253
00:20:01,750 --> 00:20:05,504
And of a somewhat more
serious offering.

254
00:20:07,908 --> 00:20:09,706
[♪ lively music]

255
00:20:11,070 --> 00:20:13,107
[♪ music stops abruptly]

256
00:20:17,750 --> 00:20:19,263
[slow, heavy beat]

257
00:20:28,429 --> 00:20:34,108
♪ I put my hand on her thigh

258
00:20:34,228 --> 00:20:36,744
♪ And she says

259
00:20:36,869 --> 00:20:39,828
♪ Do you want to try?

260
